CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old male with recurrent vertigo and fatigue.
MEDICATIONS: Os-Cal, Nexium, Lexapro, Albuterol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with 9.5 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized
by slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles are observed
in stage 2 sleep. Photic stimulation is performed after the patient has been asleep.
There is a driving response observed, though the patient is drifting in an out of sleep.
Hyperventilation produces a scant amount of background slowing.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed in this EEG. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important
consideration, a repeat study capturing one of his spells is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  	28 year old right handed woman with a possible TIA or stroke
July 2009 with left-sided numbness, weakness,  memory loss.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, Amitriptyline, Motrin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic simulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately  organized with 10.5 Hz, 30 microvolt alpha rhythm and a small amount of wicket activity. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in the record. A  normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of seizure or stroke and correlation with imaging and history may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   44 year old woman with HIV, epilepsy, bipolar disease. Seizures in April and July 2009 after patient stopped her Trileptal.

MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, Reyataz, Combivir, Seroquel, ASA, Prazosin, Dapsone, Levemir

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low voltage, but there is
an 8.5 hertz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of background beta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in slowing in the background. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta followed by an increase in theta. Hypersynchronous activity is noted in drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR: 	90 bpm

IMPRESSION:   EEG at the limits of normal.

CLINICAL CORR  ELATION: There are no epileptiform features observed. If further characterization of her epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing sleep is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old woman with visual distortions lasting 45 minutes, scintillations and visual obscurations with left-sided headache.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin,  Synthroid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG includes an
11.5 Hz 30-50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Features are drowsiness include an increase in theta as well as anterior spread of the alpha. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.   Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:	66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old right handed male with a history of epilepsy with the onset at the age of 5.  The patient has been seizure-free for approximately 5 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard  10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The study is performed with photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient begins the study in wakefulness and displays a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with 50 mV. There is higher amplitude on the left than
the right. Throughout the study, the patient transitions in and out of sleep.  During sleep a few vertex waves are noted.  There are posts and sleep spindles.  During photic stimulation there is no reactivity.  During hyperventilation an increased theta with mild slowing is noted.
HR:	N/A
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform activity is noted. A normal EEG do not exclude diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 89 year old right handed female√° with and recurrent
syncope.

MEDICATIONS: None.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low
voltage, compatible with the patient's age. There is a posterior dominant rhythm
identified, better represented on the left than the right. In this be9side portal record, is a bit more head rocking artifact. There is a small amount of background theta.

HR: 90 bpm

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for age.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in this
record. The background features are acceptable for a patient of this advanced age.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old woman with COPD, anxiety disorder with possible
seizures several days after running out of Xanax characterized by foaming of the mouth
and tongue biting. Past history of hypertension, anxiety, hepatitis C, depression and
hyponatremia.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Albuterol,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG has a great deal of muscle
and movement artifact, but underneath it, there is a 9 hertz 30 microvolts posterior
dominant rhythm and generous beta activity. Brief drowsiness is characterized by an
increase in theta.
HR:. 90bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: If epilepsy is an important consideration, please consider
a follow-up study as an outpatient to search for epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  34 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since age 14
characterized by tonic-clonic seizures in sleep but with an episode of staring in August
2009.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Stage I sleep includes an increase in beta followed by vertex waves. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. Hyperventilation produces a small increase in the amplitude of the background.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are seen.  In this individual with epilepsy, a more prolonged study capturing more extensive sleep may be helpful to identify epileptiform activity, and the beta may be due to anxiety.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  28 year old woman with episodes of leg shaking and unresponsiveness.  Bipolar disease and depression.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient appears to be tense.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD:  The background EEG includes an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with muscle artifact and beta.   Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR:   60 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The beta and the muscle artifact can be observed in an individual receiving benzodiazepines or in an anxious person.  No epileptiform features were seen.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing deeper
stages of sleep may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  38 year old right handed woman with syncope, intermittent dizziness, lightheadedness, loss of consciousness 5-7 times per week.
MEDICATIONS: Naprosyn and Elavil.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video-EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-developed 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in amplitude.  Beta activity is noted in stage I sleep.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:	55 bpm and slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. The bradycardia may be evaluated clinically.

HISTORY: 47 year old woman  with dizziness associated with movements of her head.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient declined hyperventilation. Photic simulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hz 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief epochs of drowsiness are characterized by hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing. Sleep is not sustained.   Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 	84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed.  Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old woman with episodes of body shaking and inability to speak for 1 minute. There is also right arm and leg shaking without loss of consciousness. Past medical history revealed depression, hypothyroidism, migraines and others. Also presence of cervical C3 demyelination and degenerative disease.
MEDICATIONS: Effexor, Synthroid, Ability
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation is performed. No hyperventilation due to severe COPD.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: During wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz alpha rhythm, 40 microvolt pattern. During drowsiness, there is anterior spread of this alpha rhythm as well as increase in beta activity. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform activity. Normal EEG does not exclude the presence of epilepsy. Clinical correlation is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old right handed woman with childhood epilepsy,
recurrent seizures following cerebral malaria, now seizure free, but occasional nocturnal
incontinence.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with a 10.5 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of
low voltage, frontal central beta. Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the
alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. During photic stimulation frequent blink artifact
is noted, but there are no epileptiform features.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 82 year old right handed woman with episode of confusion and verbal difficulty.
MEDICATIONS: HCTZ, Metformin, Cozaar, Aspirin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized for an adult of this age with a 10 Hz 50 mcv posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta, anterior spread of the alpha rhythm, and a few bursts of paroxysmal rhythmic slowing. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR: 82 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 62 year old woman with a stroke and intermittent episodes of left facial spasms and twitching. Past history of atherosclerosis.
MEDICATIONS: Aricept, Plavix, Metoprolol, Pravachol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm of 30 mcv with a generous amount of tow voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Frequent eye blink artifact is observed. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 90 bpm

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No significant focal features nor epileptiform features are observed. There is a single burst of slowing in the transition to drowsiness which is considered a normal finding in an adult of this age. Additional EEG recording capturing one of her spells may be of use, given the frequency of her events.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old right handed male, mentally challenged, presented with 4 episodes of loss of consciousness, with low potassium.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz posterior alpha rhythm with frequent eye flutter. Drowsiness is characterized by background slowing and POSTS. Neither hyperventilation nor photic stimulation activate the record.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were seen. A normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old right handed female with a history of seizure disorder
since age 17. The last seizure was one week ago, a tonoclonic seizure with postictal
confusion.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab with standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic simulation is performed. This was
an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11.5 Hz alpha rhythm.Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta with some central theta.
Photic stimulation elicits supraharmonic driving.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does
not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. In this individual with what sounds like a
generalized epilepsy, hyperventilation was not performed. Please return the patient to
the lab for a more prolonged study, capturing deeper stages of sleep and including
hyperventilation.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old woman with epilepsy for the last 21 years, but seizure free for the last 2 years, history of a sleep disturbance.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and sleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage. There is a symmetric reactive 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Mu rhythm is identified, as is some wicket activity. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. During photic stimulation eye flutter is asymmetric, but a symmetric driving response is noted.

HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no focal nor epileptiform features observed. There are multiple normal variants. The somewhat asymmetric eye flutter may suggest that electrode placement may have been suboptimal. If there are any questions a repeat study with specifically eye leads and a study all the way to stage 2 sleep can be helpful to characterize this individual's epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old right handed female with alcoholic cirrhosis with new
onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Done listed in chart
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep
record. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm as
well as a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is
characterized by an increase in. background theta. Hyperventilation produces a small
amount of theta. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. A normal EEG
does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy, and if the seizure is an important
consideration, a repeat tracing capturing sleep may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old male with left-sided stroke with right-sided weakness
and a seizure January 2010.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in Jab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation is performed.
This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm
with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Photic stimulation elicits
scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed today. To more
completely characterize this individual's epilepsy, comparison with the previous 2005
EEG or a repeat study capturing in sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 79 year old right woman with a stroke 20 years ago and dysarthria, 5 mm aneurysm.

MEDICATIONS: Klonopin, Sertraline, Verapamil, Lisinopril, Lipitor

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG demonstrates a 9 Hz, 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. There is a small amount of frontocentral theta. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits a subtle driving response. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for age.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing sleep may be considered. Given the magnitude of chronic ischemic changes the EEG finding are quite modest.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 49 year old gentleman with epilepsy, seizure free for the last 10 years but with inappropriate behavior, lower extremity weakness, and then a seizure in the Emergency Room waiting area.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lasix, Lisinopril

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed for this very drowsy individual.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is asleep through almost the entire EEG. He awakens really only for photic stimulation at which point an 8.8 Hz alpha rhythm is identified. The remainder of the drowsy record is a low voltage, slow pattern. In drowsiness, there is some occipital delta identified bilaterally but with a bit of shifting slowing in the occipital regions.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features. The excessive drowsiness may be correlated clinically.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 44 year old right handed male with past history of seizure-like episodes, none recently.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an sleep deprived EEG, awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In sleep, there is a beta frequency background with occasional vertex waves. In wakefulness, there is a 12Hz alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation produces bilateral driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.

HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION; This is the second normal EEG for this individual. If the patient is thought to have epilepsy, a more prolonged study may be helpful. Alternatively capturing one of his spells may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 68 year old gentleman with 2 seizures, the first 9 years ago and
the second 1 year ago.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. Neither hyperventilation nor photic stimulation activate the
record.The patient remains quite drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior
dominant rhythm but the patient transitions relatively quickly back into a drowsy state.
Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm with more of a theta
frequency pattern followed by vertex waves.
HR: 55 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Clinical correction
to determine why the patient is so sleepy may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 65 year old right-handed woman with 3 episodes of 10 to 15 seconds of aphasia over the past 5 years.
MEDICATIONS: Zoloft, Simvastatin, Aspirin, Hyzaar
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. There is also a small amount of 7 to 8 Hz theta frequency activity. Rare, left temporal mixed theta delta is identified as the patient transitions into drowsiness with a small amount of rhythmic mid temporal theta with drowsiness. Other features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing and attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Neither hyperventilation nor photic stimulation significantly activate the record.
HR: 88 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the normal limits for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features identified. Because of the scant amount of theta in the background, a follow-up study may be helpful if this individual continues to have cognitive difficulty.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old male who fell and hit his head November 2009 with an occipital skull fracture consequently developed loss of taste, loss of smell, impaired memory, headaches which are left frontal headaches and spreading to the occipital region, also paroxysmal dizziness, hypertension, and diabetes.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Insulin and Seroquel,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes symmetric reactive alpha rhythm of 10 Hz and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Single electrode artifact is noted at T4 throughout the record. Neither hyperventilation nor photic stimulation significantly activate the record. Stage 1 sleep includes vertexes, K-complexes, spindles and posts.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified in this record. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 63 year old woman with memory impairment and dizziness.
MEDICATIONS: Motrin, Simvastatin, Benadryl, Klonopin, Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation were performed. The patient is quite anxious.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10.5 Hertz 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Features of drowsiness include an increase in theta. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response. Hyperventilation increases the amplitude.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were noted. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old left handed woman with new onset seizures. The patient was watching television and saw a butterfly come out at her, screamed and then had a tonic, clonic seizure. Family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Vitamins.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in amplitude of the background followed by rhythmic theta and vertex waves when the patient becomes sleepy. Photic stimulation elicits generous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The generous driving response described above is not pathological. No epileptiform features are observed, but if epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study which may be sleep deprived or a 1 hour EEG may be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 59 year old right handed male with syncope, encephalopathy and new-onset seizures with right-sided jerking. Past history of a gunshot wound to the right jaw.

MEDICATIONS: Lovenox, Hydralazine, Protonix, ASA, Percocet

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is described as agitated.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is a 10.3 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Features of drowsiness including increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Heart rate 72-90 bpm.

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed; however, sleep was not achieved. Please consider a repeat study in the lab if further information is needed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 21 year old left handed male with new onset tonic-clonic
seizures 1.5 years ago. Headaches prior to the seizures. Seizure-free for the last 6
months.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized
with symmetric, reactive, 10.3 Hz alpha rhythm of 50 microvolts. There is a
small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed
early-on in the record producing an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic
stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed but evaluation for
the irregular heart rate may be warranted. If epilepsy is an important consideration,
please consider a repeat study capturing sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 41 year old right handed male with a single seizure in early
February 2009.

MEDICATIONS: None.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness this a well organized record with a
10.7 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.
Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing. Vertex waves and posts
are noted in stage 1 sleep with spindles and stage 2 sleep. Hyperventilation produces
more of a drowsy pattern. The patient drifts off to sleep after hyperventilation. Photic
stimulation is remarkable for scant driving.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second normal EEG for this individual. A
normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 22 year old right handed female with complaint of generalized
headaches 4-5 times per week with cerebral palsy, cerebellar damage, ataxia, scoliosis,
and asthma.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Albuterol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm,
which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. It is approximately 40 microvolts in
amplitude. It is similar in both right and left. Drowsiness is characterized by
background slowing and POSTS. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of
the background. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Eye artifact is identified in the temporal region in the transition to sleep, but there is no focal slowing or sharp waves.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
The amplitude asymmetry seen in the previous study was not identified today, but this
was technically a better study. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a prolonged
monitoring study can be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed female with past medical history of seizures since young adulthood. Last seizure was approximately 2 weeks ago. Patient is a poor historian, but blacks out with inability to talk.

MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background had a 9.5 Hz alpha activity, photic stimulation produced driving. Hyperventilation produces an increases in amplitude.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Clinical correlation is needed. May want to consider a long-term monitoring EEG or Digitrace to identify epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old right handed female with a history of seizure onset on October 9, was general tonoclonic activity. Her last seizure was one week ago. Patient also has a history of depression and arthritis.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Gabapentin, Lyrica, Lamictal, Asacol, Prozac, Ambien.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The EEG in the awake state is well-organized. The background consists of alpha but is less vigorous. Photic stimulation was performed, and it produced supraharmonic driving. Hyperventilation was performed, also. There was no seizure activity, no focal or epileptiform features.
HR: N/A
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform activity or focal features were found. Absence of epileptiform activity does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. Additional EEG may be useful to capture any epileptiform activity. May want to consider outpatient DigiTrace.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old right handed male with recurrent dizzy spells with loss of consciousness and tongue biting.
MEDICATIONS: Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10 Hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness includes rhythmic theta. CLINICAL HISTORY:  25 year old right handed female with episode of shaking, increased heart rate, rapid breathing followed by left arm shaking which progressed to the whole body.  The patient awake and aware of the episode.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal single lead EEG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTY:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation produced no abnormal discharges, however, see below for photic stimulation.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  During photic stimulation, the patient started having slow movements of her head side to side then started twitching her upper extremities and moving her body towards the right side and appeared to be unresponsive to commands.  This episode lasted for a period of about 40 seconds and then she remained with her eyes closed and appeared to be slightly more responsive.  Minutes later, photic stimulation was performed again after she had opened her eyes and appeared to have followed commands.  At that point she started jerking her left shoulder slowly, then trembling her upper extremities and again falling towards the right side of the seat.  This second episode lasted for about approximately a minute and 20 seconds.  During both episodes, the EEG revealed a normal awake background with no epileptiform abnormalities and no EEG correlate to this behavior described above.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG with two episodes of shaking during photic stimulation with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG with no seizures or epileptiform discharges.  The episodes captured above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with nonepileptic events.  No seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed man, with a history of seizures with Xanax withdrawal, anxiety, and hypertension, presents for episodes of strange things in mouth with quick recall of events.  He is here for classification of epileptic versus non-epileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.  Continues spike wave detection and seizure detection software was used to review the event, along with the patient's alarms, nurses notes, and clinical notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of frontal central beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage 1, stage 2, and deep stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENT:  During the recording the patient had 5 events where he would suddenly start shaking his head from side to side.  Sometimes towards the left and sometimes toward the right irregularly while becoming unresponsive and remaining so for minutes at time, sometimes for more than 5-10 minutes, and intermittently starting and stopping the behavior.  These  episodes, the first one which occurred at 3:28 p.m., the second one occurred at 9:23 p.m., the third one occurred around 2:40 a.m., and another one at 7:51 a.m., and the last one at 8:48 am had no EEG correlate other than a muscle artifact and afterwards there was normal posterior dominant rhythm seen, all consistent with nonepileptic events.
SEIZURES:  None
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The episodes captured above with head shaking had no EEG correlate.  As such, they are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic events. Please note that this patient had previous records which showed left temporal sharp waves.  This was not seen during this admission.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  18 year old right handed female syncopal spell lasting 25 seconds.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and a sleep record in very drowsy individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, exceeding 70 mV with posterior slow waves of youth.  In drowsiness there is hypersynchronous rhythmic higher amplitude theta frequency activity ‚Äúhypnogogic‚Äù, ‚Äúhypersynchrony‚Äù.  There were 1 or 2 points of head rocking artifact and there were 1-2 bursts which are slightly asynchronous. Hyperventilation produces hypersynchronous rhythmic high amplitude, somewhat sharply contoured theta frequency activity, but no definitive spike and wave activity. The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Other features of drowsiness include the hypersynchronous rhythmic theta.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG demonstrates multiple normal variants for a young adult.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There was no definitive spike and wave activity, although hyperventilation did produce some rhythmic high amplitude theta.  There were a handful of slightly asynchronous bursts as the patient transitions to drowsiness.  If absence seizures are an important consideration, a repeat fasting EEG, perhaps with a second hyperventilation session maybe helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with epilepsy since age 12.  Subsequent cocaine dependence.  After a seizure, patient became violent. The patient asked the technologist if photic stimulation would produce 1 of his typical seizures.  The technologist told him that, that was a possibility.  The patient subsequently had 1 of typical behaviors during photic stimulation, but after the photic stimulation had stopped.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a scant amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the EEG and produces and increase an amplitude of the background.  Vertex waves and POSTS are observed in stage 1 sleep with brief stage 2 sleep.  The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation and transitioning in and out of sleep during photic stimulation.
The patient had an event during photic stimulation.  The patient was drowsy prior to photic stimulations, the patient was waking up, although there were brief transitions in and out of sleep.
The patient was awake at the end of the 11 Hz stimuli, when the behavior occurred, he sat up abruptly.  His eyes were dilated, he was moving back and forth and his heart rate increased briefly to 150 BPM.
Although the audio was not working, the patient was able to communicate during the event.
There were no epileptiform features noted during the event.  No postictal features were identified.
Heart rate 78-150 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  The EEG is normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient had an unusual behavior.  The patient was clearly awake for several seconds prior to the event, but he had been drifting in and out of sleep.  The event had no epileptiform features, but a link either to a sleep-related disorder or a psychiatric illness may be considered.

He has multiple events per day, most of them are nocturnal.  Last such seizure was on 01/07/2013.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin extended release 200 mg twice a day and Tegretol extended release 200 mg b.i.d.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), vertex waves and sleep complexes are captured.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort and produces no significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:  No epileptiform discharges to stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 27-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 48-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 5, the patient experienced 3 seizures on January 4.  Seizures began with aura of tingling in the mouth followed by a loss of consciousness, foaming at the mouth, and post-ictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not performed but photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Much of the EEG includes drowsiness, stage I and stage II sleep, with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS noted in stage II sleep.  The tech was able to awaken the patient prior to photic stimulation at which point a well organized background with 10 Hz alpha rhythm was noted.  Photic stimulation did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate:  78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  In this individual with a recent exacerbation of seizures, additional EEG recording may be of use to capture epileptiform activity.

There is low amplitude diffuse beta-activity, which is distributed symmetrically, stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts and stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background, and photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy if seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful. CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 28-year-old woman with daily staring spells lasting less than a minute.  Also, right sided facial pain since she fell from a horse in 2010.  Normal MRI.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and generous beta.
The patient seems to be quite drowsy with hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  Rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness was noted with the characteristic 5 Hz flat top shape with rhythmic theta from the right temporal region.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response.  There was a fair amount of muscle artifact during photic stimulation.
Hyperventilation elicited paroxysmal, high amplitude slowing.  There is a small amount of shifting slowing noted in hyperventilation but the patient also appears to be quite drowsy, transitioning into sleep during hyperventilation.
Heart rate:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Rhythmic with temporal theta of drowsiness is a normal finding and is considered a normal variant.  There is a somewhat asynchronous hyperventilation response.  This is a nonspecific finding and is not necessarily pathological.  In this patient with episodes of staring, perhaps a more prolonged spell looking for additional drowsy bursts may be of value.
